<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<task id="003" project="spaarkeai-compose-r1">
  <metadata>
    <title>Spike #3 — SPE check-out/check-in + Document promotion-on-Save</title>
    <phase>Phase 0: Spikes</phase>
    <status>not-started</status>
    <estimated-hours>4</estimated-hours>
    <tags>spike, backend, bff-api, spe, prototype</tags>
    <rigor-hint>STANDARD</rigor-hint>
    <parallel-group>A</parallel-group>
    <parallel-safe>true</parallel-safe>
    <dependencies>none</dependencies>
  </metadata>

  <prompt>
    Validate two binding R1 mechanisms: (1) the per-user single-session lock model via SPE check-out/check-in plus a session heartbeat (default proposed: 15 minutes idle → auto-release); and (2) the ephemeral-doc Path B Save flow where the first Save creates a `sprk_document` record idempotently. Prove both via a working BFF prototype against a real SPE container. Output proposes the final heartbeat interval and validates idempotency under multi-click conditions. This spike unlocks Phase 3 (SPE plumbing) and Phase 4 (Save/promotion).
  </prompt>

  <role>
    Senior .NET developer experienced with Microsoft Graph SDK, SharePoint Embedded, Minimal API patterns, and idempotent endpoint design. Familiar with Spaarke's existing Graph client factory and BFF authorization model.
  </role>

  <goal>
    A working BFF prototype demonstrating: SPE check-out lock acquired on Compose session open, heartbeat keeping the lock alive, auto-release after configurable idle threshold, and ephemeral-doc Save creating a `sprk_document` record with verified idempotency (N concurrent Save calls → 1 record). Output published as `notes/spikes/spike-3-spe-checkout-promotion.md` with recommended heartbeat interval.
  </goal>

  <inputs>
    <file purpose="design-spec">projects/spaarkeai-compose-r1/spec.md</file>
    <file purpose="design-working">projects/spaarkeai-compose-r1/design.md</file>
    <file purpose="project-plan">projects/spaarkeai-compose-r1/plan.md</file>
    <file purpose="project-context">projects/spaarkeai-compose-r1/CLAUDE.md</file>
    <file purpose="task-index">projects/spaarkeai-compose-r1/tasks/TASK-INDEX.md</file>
  </inputs>

  <constraints>
    <constraint source="project">Per design.md §14 row 4: per-user single-session lock via SPE check-out. Orphan locks released via heartbeat (proposed default: 15 min idle).</constraint>
    <constraint source="project">Per design.md §8: first Save creates the `sprk_document` record idempotently. Multiple Save clicks before/after MUST NOT create duplicate Document records.</constraint>
    <constraint source="project">Per design.md §10.5 Placement Justification: all SPE/Dataverse work is in `Sprk.Bff.Api` — no microservice, no plugin.</constraint>
    <constraint source="ADR-001">Use Minimal API + endpoint filters; no Azure Functions.</constraint>
    <constraint source="ADR-008">Authorization via endpoint filters / `RequireAuthorization()` — not middleware.</constraint>
    <constraint source="project">Prototype code lives in `notes/spikes/` ONLY — throwaway; production endpoints implemented in Phase 3.</constraint>
  </constraints>

  <knowledge>
    <topic>spe, graph-sdk, bff, idempotency, checkout</topic>
    <files>
      <file>projects/spaarkeai-compose-r1/spec.md</file>
      <file>projects/spaarkeai-compose-r1/design.md</file>
      <file>docs/architecture/SPAARKEAI-WORKSPACE-ARCHITECTURE.md</file>
      <file>src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Api/FileAccessEndpoints.cs</file>
      <file>.claude/constraints/bff-extensions.md</file>
    </files>
  </knowledge>

  <context>
    <background>
      Single-editor mode is the R1 collaboration model (Q4 resolution; CRDT deferred to R5+). SPE provides check-out as the native primitive — but check-out alone is not enough; an orphan lock from a crashed browser would block re-entry forever, so a heartbeat with auto-release is required. The 15-minute default is a proposal; this spike empirically refines it. Separately, the ephemeral Path B (upload from Assistant, no `sprk_document` yet) Save flow MUST be idempotent — duplicate Document records would corrupt the matter knowledge graph and the AI search index.
    </background>
    <related-work>
      <item>design.md §14 row 4 (multi-tab single-session lock decision)</item>
      <item>design.md §8 (Document source — Save-promotion rule)</item>
      <item>design.md §12 BFF Surface (`POST /api/compose/document/{id}/checkout|checkin|promote`)</item>
    </related-work>
  </context>

  <steps>
    <step order="0" name="Context check + load knowledge">
      Verify context &lt; 70%. Read design.md §§8, 10.5, 12, 14 row 4. Load `.claude/constraints/bff-extensions.md` (binding pre-merge checklist). Examine `FileAccessEndpoints.cs` for existing Graph client usage patterns to mirror.
    </step>
    <step order="1" name="Scaffold BFF spike endpoint group">
      Create `notes/spikes/spike-3-prototype/` with a minimal slice of BFF code (NOT yet wired into Program.cs) exposing: `POST /spike/checkout`, `POST /spike/heartbeat`, `POST /spike/checkin`, `POST /spike/promote`. Use the existing `GraphClientFactory` pattern.
    </step>
    <step order="2" name="Implement check-out + heartbeat + auto-release">
      Wrap Graph SDK check-out; track per-user lock with last-heartbeat timestamp in memory (or Redis if available). Background task auto-releases locks after idle threshold (parameterize 5/10/15/30 minutes for testing).
    </step>
    <step order="3" name="Test multi-tab/multi-session conflict UX">
      Simulate user opening same doc in two sessions: second call MUST return a conflict response signaling "open in another Compose session" with options Go-to-other / Force-close. Verify force-close releases prior lock cleanly.
    </step>
    <step order="4" name="Implement promote-on-Save with idempotency">
      `POST /spike/promote` creates `sprk_document` record bound to SPE drive-item id. Use upsert-by-spe-drive-item-id semantics (NOT generic create). Test: fire 5 concurrent promote calls → assert exactly 1 record exists.
    </step>
    <step order="5" name="Empirically tune heartbeat interval">
      Run sessions at 5/10/15/30 min idle thresholds. Recommend final interval based on: user-friction vs orphan-lock-recovery latency trade-off. Document rationale.
    </step>
    <step order="6" name="Write spike report">
      Write `notes/spikes/spike-3-spe-checkout-promotion.md` with: prototype location, recommended heartbeat interval (+ rationale), idempotency proof (concurrent-call test result), conflict UX wire-state machine, and any open issues for Phase 3 production implementation.
    </step>
    <step order="7" name="Update TASK-INDEX + close">
      Update `projects/spaarkeai-compose-r1/tasks/TASK-INDEX.md`: mark task 003 as ✅. Update `current-task.md`. Report completion.
    </step>
  </steps>

  <tools>
    <tool name="dotnet">Build and test the spike BFF slice</tool>
    <tool name="git">Version control</tool>
  </tools>

  <outputs>
    <output type="prototype" ephemeral="true">projects/spaarkeai-compose-r1/notes/spikes/spike-3-prototype/</output>
    <output type="report">projects/spaarkeai-compose-r1/notes/spikes/spike-3-spe-checkout-promotion.md</output>
    <output type="docs">projects/spaarkeai-compose-r1/tasks/TASK-INDEX.md (status update)</output>
  </outputs>

  <acceptance-criteria>
    <criterion testable="true">Check-out endpoint acquires SPE lock on a real test container; check-in releases it cleanly.</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">Heartbeat auto-release triggers at the configured idle threshold; orphan locks recover automatically.</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">Multi-session conflict path returns expected response with Go-to-other / Force-close options.</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">Promote-on-Save is idempotent under ≥5 concurrent calls — exactly one `sprk_document` record created.</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">Spike report names final recommended heartbeat interval with empirical rationale; TASK-INDEX.md status for task 003 is ✅.</criterion>
  </acceptance-criteria>

  <execution>
    <skill>.claude/skills/task-execute/SKILL.md</skill>
  </execution>
</task>
